    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided MD&A and financial statement excerpts, here is a detailed description of the Space segment's operations, financial drivers, and metrics:\n\n### Overview\nThe Space segment designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Dragon, and the in-development Starship) to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space for commercial and government customers. The segment flies to LEO, MEO, GEO, lunar, interplanetary trajectories, and the International Space Station (ISS). \n\n### Revenue Drivers & Recognition\nSpace segment revenue is derived from fixed-price contracts, categorized into two streams:\n*   **Launch Services:** Revenue from deploying payloads to intended orbits for commercial and government customers. Contracts range from one to five years. Revenue is recognized at a **point in time** (upon launch or deployment) due to the interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs.\n*   **Launch and Development:** Revenue from the development of spacecraft and provision of launch/mission services for government agency space programs. Contracts range from one to fourteen years. Revenue is recognized **over time** using the cost-to-cost input method, as the performance creates an asset with no alternative use and the company has an enforceable right to payment.\n*   **Inter-segment Allocations:** The Space segment does not recognize inter-segment revenue for launches of its own Starlink satellites; those costs are capitalized in the Connectivity segment. The segment currently allocates significant launch capacity to the Connectivity segment and expects to allocate a significant amount to the AI segment in the future. \n*   **Growth Expectations:** Space revenue growth is expected to be lower than total company revenue growth because internal businesses are absorbing most of the growth in launch capacity. Launch and Development is expected to represent a larger portion of Space revenue due to long-term government contracts.\n\n### Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)\nThe Space segment uses two primary operational metrics that grow more rapidly than segment revenue because they include internal constellation deployments:\n*   **Mass to Orbit:** Total kilograms of payload deployed to orbit (excluding failed or scrubbed attempts). \n    *   *2023:* 1,210 metric tons (205 customer / 1,005 internal)\n    *   *2024:* 1,699 metric tons (282 customer / 1,418 internal)\n    *   *2025:* 2,213 metric tons (312 customer / 1,901 internal)\n    *   *Q1 2025:* 450 metric tons\n    *   *Q1 2026:* 556 metric tons\n*   **Launches:** Sum of all successful orbital and flight tests, including internal Starlink deployments, development tests, and third-party customer launches. \n\n### Launch Cadence & Mission Counts\n*   **Falcon 9 Cadence:** Falcon 9 is the most active orbital launch vehicle today, with approximately 620 orbital space launches as of March 31, 2026, and an over 99% mission success rate. Falcon 9 contributes an average capacity of 13 metric tons per mission.\n    *   *2024:* 134 total Falcon launches\n    *   *2025:* 165 total Falcon 9 launches (157 using flight-proven boosters)\n    *   *Q1 2026:* 40 Falcon rockets launched (39 flight-proven)\n*   **Future Transition:** The company expects Falcon 9 launches to decrease over time as it transitions to Starship. Starship V3 is expected to carry 100 metric tons of payload, with future generations designed to double that capacity.\n\n### Cost Structure & Capital Intensity\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** Includes second stages flown (non-reusable), launch operations/overhead, depreciation, employee compensation, engineering costs, inventory excess/obsolescence, and shared production costs. Cost of revenue is expected to increase in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue based on the mix of Launch Services and Launch & Development.\n*   **Capital Intensity (Reusable vs. Non-Reusable):** \n    *   *Reusable components:* Boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, and Dragon capsules are classified as Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E) and depreciated to cost of revenue.\n    *   *Non-reusable components:* Second stages are recorded to cost of revenue when launched or assigned.\n    *   *Starship:* Currently in the development stage. A majority of costs are expensed to R&D as incurred, and Raptor engines are expensed when used in test flights. Once commercialized (by delivering payload to orbit), Starship costs will generally be capitalized and depreciated in the cost of revenue of the associated payload's segment.\n*   **R&D Expenses:** Mainly relate to Starship development (test flight hardware, Raptor engines, compensation, tooling, depreciation, overhead). R&D is expected to increase in 2026 to invest in Starship commercialization and moderate once it is commercialized.\n*   **SG&A:** Includes allocated employee compensation for sales, facilities, legal, finance, IT, security systems, and facility-level overhead.\n\n### Backlog & Deferred Revenue\n*   Deferred revenue primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise/government contracts.\n*   Total deferred revenue as of December 31, 2024, was **$10,179 million** (of which $4,080 million was recognized as revenue in 2025).\n*   Total deferred revenue as of December 31, 2025, was **$12,116 million**.\n\n### Customer Concentration\nThe segment serves a diversified base of commercial and government customers. Specific key contracts and customers highlighted include:\n*   **NASA:** Extended contract for additional Cargo Resupply Services (CRS) missions to the International Space Station.\n*   **U.S. Department of War:** Increased revenue from a specific contract.\n\n### Disclosed Financials & Contract Values\n*   **2025 Full Year:** Revenue of **$4,086 million** (up 7.6% or $290 million from 2024, driven by a $298 million increase in Launch & Development). Loss from operations of **$(657) million**. Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$653 million** (down $501 million from 2024 due to accelerated Starship investment). Funded **$3,004 million** in R&D for Starship.\n*   **Q1 2026:** Revenue of **$619 million** (down $246 million from Q1 2025 due to lower Launch Services missions and timing of government work). Loss from operations of **$(662) million**. Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(351) million**. Funded **$930 million** in R&D for Starship.",
