    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided document chunks, here is a detailed description of the Connectivity segment (Starlink), including its revenue drivers, KPIs, cost structure, capital intensity, and operational metrics:\n\n### 1. Revenue Drivers\nThe Connectivity segment generates revenue primarily through subscription fees from consumer subscribers, as well as enterprise and government contracts. Specifically, revenue is generated from:\n*   **Consumer Broadband:** Monthly subscription fees based on geographic market and download speed, recognized ratably over the service period. This is typically accompanied by a one-time sale of a Starlink Kit (terminal). Revenue growth is driven by Starlink Subscriber growth, partially offset by declining ARPU due to international expansion and lower-priced service plans.\n*   **Enterprise and Government:** Revenue is generated through contracts structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity, or on a percentage-of-completion basis. This includes aviation, maritime, land mobility, and fixed-site enterprise businesses, as well as long-term government contracts for Starshield (a secure satellite network).\n*   **Mobile Connectivity:** The company charges Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) either a fixed fee or a per-mobile user fee-based amount, typically passed through to the customer via the carrier.\n\n### 2. Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)\n**Starlink Subscribers:**\n*   **Definition:** The number of unique Service Lines at the end of a period. It includes Personal (Residential, Roam) and Business (Local Priority, Global Priority) plans, but excludes managed enterprise and government customers.\n*   **Disclosed Counts:**\n    *   Q1 2026 (Three months ended March 31, 2026): 10.3 million (up 105% YoY)\n    *   Q1 2025 (Three months ended March 31, 2025): 5.0 million (up 91% YoY)\n    *   FY 2025: 8.9 million\n    *   FY 2024: 4.4 million\n    *   FY 2023: 2.3 million\n*   **Growth:** 104.7% growth in Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025; 99.9% growth in FY 2025 vs. FY 2024; 96.5% growth in FY 2024 vs. FY 2023.\n\n**Starlink Subscriber ARPU (Average Revenue Per User):**\n*   **Definition:** Service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers during the period, divided by the average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period, divided by the number of months in the period.\n*   **Disclosed ARPU:**\n    *   Q1 2026: $66 per month\n    *   Q1 2025: $86 per month\n    *   FY 2025: $81 per month\n    *   FY 2024: $91 per month\n    *   FY 2023: $99 per month\n*   **Trend:** ARPU has been steadily declining (e.g., a 22.9% decline in Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025, and an 11.2% decline in FY 2025 vs. FY 2024). This is primarily due to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans. The company\'s strategy prioritizes driving sustainable revenue growth and expanding margins over prioritizing ARPU increases.\n\n**Mobile Connectivity Metrics:**\n*   Satellite-to-mobile texting and over-the-top voice services are provided to approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices across approximately 30 countries (as of March 31, 2026).\n\n**Network Performance:**\n*   Median latency of approximately 25 milliseconds.\n*   Median download speed of 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users (as of March 31, 2026).\n\n### 3. Satellite Deployment Plans & Constellation Status\n*   **Current Constellation:** As of March 31, 2026, SpaceX had approximately 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO), operating across 164 countries, territories, and other markets (home to more than 3.3 billion people).\n*   **Mobile Satellites:** The "V1" mobile constellation consists of approximately 650 V1 Mobile satellites in orbit, currently supporting light data, SMS, and over-the-top voice. The company is developing comprehensive satellite-to-mobile services, including broadband data, IoT, and 5G connectivity.\n*   **Launch Capacity Allocation:** The Space segment allocates a significant amount of its launch capacity to the Connectivity segment to deploy Starlink satellites. The costs associated with these launches are capitalized within the Connectivity segment and depreciated over time. \n\n### 4. Cost Structure\nThe Connectivity segment’s cost of revenue includes:\n*   **Depreciation:** Inclusive of launch, satellite, and ground infrastructure costs. This has been a major driver of cost increases due to the growing number of Starlink flights and satellites placed into orbit.\n*   **Starlink Kit Costs:** Hardware costs for terminals. Higher volume spend on kits has driven cost of revenue increases due to higher kit deliveries. *(Note: Specific per-unit terminal manufacturing costs are not disclosed, but kit costs are explicitly listed as a component of cost of revenue).*\n*   **Operating Expenses:** Ground operating expenses, customer support and installation costs, payment processor fees, freight/shipping and handling costs, warranty expense, inventory excess and obsolescence, and customs and duties.\n*   **Employee Compensation:** Salaries, benefits, and share-based compensation for engineering and operations teams.\n*   **R&D Expenses:** Driven by next-generation production development of satellites, Starlink Kits, and ground equipment.\n\n### 5. Capital Intensity\nThe Connectivity segment is highly capital-intensive, requiring significant ongoing investment to scale the constellation and ground infrastructure.\n*   **Capital Expenditures (CapEx):** For the three months ended March 31, 2026, capital expenditures for the Connectivity segment were $1,332 million.\n*   **Capitalized Costs:** The company capitalizes launch and satellite costs, which flow into depreciation over time, creating a substantial fixed asset base.\n*   **Financial Scale:** Despite the capital intensity and declining ARPU, the segment is highly profitable on an operating basis. For Q1 2026, the segment generated $3,257 million in revenue, $1,188 million in income from operations, and $2,087 million in Segment Adjusted EBITDA. For the full year 2025, it generated $11,387 million in revenue, $4,423 million in income from operations, and $7,168 million in Segment Adjusted EBITDA.',
