    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Segment-Level Financial Performance: FY2023–Q1 2026\n\n## 1. Consolidated Data Summary\n\n### Space Segment\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 (for reference) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Revenue** | $3,557M | $3,796M | $4,086M | $619M | $865M |\n| **Income (loss) from operations** | $(1)M | $21M | $(657)M | $(662)M | $(70)M |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | $997M | $1,154M | $653M | $(351)M | $224M |\n\n### Connectivity Segment\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 (for reference) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Revenue** | $3,869M | $7,599M | $11,387M | $3,257M | $2,475M |\n| **Income (loss) from operations** | $469M | $2,006M | $4,423M | $1,188M | $1,033M |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | $1,602M | $3,849M | $7,168M | $2,087M | $1,618M |\n\n### AI Segment\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 (for reference) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Revenue** | $2,961M | $2,620M | $3,201M | $818M | $727M |\n| **Income (loss) from operations** | $(3,973)M | $(1,561)M | $(6,355)M | $(2,469)M | $(936)M |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | $1,222M | $347M | $(1,237)M | $(609)M | $(112)M |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Revenue Growth Rate Comparison\n\n| Period | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **FY2023 → FY2024** | +6.7% | +96.4% | −11.5% |\n| **FY2024 → FY2025** | +7.6% | +49.8% | +22.2% |\n| **Q1 2025 → Q1 2026** | −28.4% | +31.6% | +12.5% |\n\n### Key observations:\n- **Connectivity** is the clear growth engine, nearly doubling revenue from 2023 to 2024 and growing another ~50% in 2025, driven by Starlink subscriber growth, enterprise adoption, and network efficiency gains.\n- **Space** revenue growth has been modest in absolute terms (high single digits annually), and actually declined year-over-year in Q1 2026 (from $865M to $619M), reflecting the company\'s stated strategy of allocating more launch capacity internally to Connectivity and AI rather than to external customers.\n- **AI** revenue declined from 2023 to 2024 but rebounded in 2025, with Q1 2026 showing continued sequential improvement over Q1 2025.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Operating Income/Loss Trend Analysis\n\n### Space\n- Operating results hovered near breakeven in 2023 ($(1)M) and 2024 ($21M), then deteriorated sharply to a $(657)M loss in 2025 and $(662)M in Q1 2026 alone.\n- The primary driver is escalating R&D expense for the next-generation Starship program: $3,004M in 2025 and $930M in Q1 2026. The company characterizes Starship as "the key enabler of our long-term growth strategy."\n- Q1 2026\'s operating loss ($662M) already matches the full-year 2025 loss ($657M), signaling that Starship investment intensity is accelerating.\n\n### Connectivity\n- Operating income has grown explosively and consistently: $469M → $2,006M → $4,423M, representing YoY growth of 327% (2023→2024) and 120.4% (2024→2025).\n- Q1 2026 operating income of $1,188M is up 15.0% from Q1 2025\'s $1,033M, suggesting growth is continuing but at a more moderate pace than the full-year 2025 surge.\n- This segment is the sole profit center at the operating-income level and cross-subsidizes the other two segments.\n\n### AI\n- The AI segment has generated operating losses every year, with the loss widening dramatically from $(1,561)M in 2024 to $(6,355)M in 2025.\n- The FY2023 loss of $(3,973)M was heavily inflated by a $3,775M impairment charge; excluding that, the underlying operating loss was approximately $(198)M.\n- Q1 2026\'s operating loss of $(2,469)M is already 2.6× the Q1 2025 loss of $(936)M, indicating accelerating investment.\n- The company explicitly states it will "prioritize growth and investment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure," signaling losses are expected to persist.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Segment Adjusted EBITDA Trend Analysis\n\n| Segment | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Space** | $997M | $1,154M | $653M | $(351)M | $224M |\n| **Connectivity** | $1,602M | $3,849M | $7,168M | $2,087M | $1,618M |\n| **AI** | $1,222M | $347M | $(1,237)M | $(609)M | $(112)M |\n| **Total Reportable Segments** | $3,821M | $5,350M | $6,584M | $1,127M | $1,730M |\n\n### Key observations:\n\n**Space:**\n- Adjusted EBITDA peaked in 2024 at $1,154M, declined 43% to $653M in 2025, and turned negative in Q1 2026 at $(351)M — a stark reversal from the $224M generated in Q1 2025.\n- The Q1 2026 deterioration is driven by lower revenue ($619M vs. $865M in Q1 2025) combined with sustained high R&D spending ($930M for Starship).\n- Depreciation and amortization has been steadily rising ($571M → $637M → $757M → $166M in Q1 2026 alone), reflecting growing fixed-asset base from launch infrastructure.\n\n**Connectivity:**\n- Adjusted EBITDA has grown every year: $1,602M → $3,849M (+140%) → $7,168M (+86.2%).\n- Q1 2026 Adjusted EBITDA of $2,087M represents 29.1% growth over Q1 2025\'s $1,618M.\n- The segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA margin on revenue was approximately 63% in 2025, up from 51% in 2024 and 41% in 2023 — demonstrating strong operating leverage as the Starlink constellation scales.\n- This segment alone generated more Adjusted EBITDA in 2025 ($7,168M) than the total company\'s consolidated Adjusted EBITDA ($6,584M), meaning it more than fully offsets the losses in Space and AI.\n\n**AI:**\n- Adjusted EBITDA has declined every year: $1,222M → $347M → $(1,237)M.\n- The 2023 figure was bolstered by the large impairment add-back ($3,775M); without it, underlying Adjusted EBITDA would have been deeply negative.\n- Q1 2026 Adjusted EBITDA of $(609)M is 5.4× worse than Q1 2025\'s $(112)M, reflecting ramping depreciation from massive capital expenditures ($7,723M in Q1 2026 alone, compared to $2,567M in Q1 2025).\n- The segment\'s depreciation and amortization has grown from $1,180M (2023) to $1,679M (2024) to $3,568M (2025), and was already $1,493M in Q1 2026 — annualizing to roughly $5,972M, which would represent a ~67% increase over 2025.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Cross-Segment Profitability Comparison\n\n### FY2025 Adjusted EBITDA Margin (Adjusted EBITDA / Revenue)\n\n| Segment | FY2025 Margin |\n|---|---|\n| Space | 16.0% |\n| Connectivity | 63.0% |\n| AI | (38.6)% |\n| **Consolidated** | **35.3%** |\n\n### Q1 2026 Adjusted EBITDA Margin (Annualized Run-Rate Context)\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 Margin |\n|---|---|\n| Space | (56.7)% |\n| Connectivity | 64.1% |\n| AI | (74.4)% |\n| **Consolidated** | **24.0%** |\n\n---\n\n## 6. Capital Expenditure Context\n\nCapital expenditure patterns reinforce the strategic narrative:\n\n| Segment | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Space | $1,497M | $2,032M | $3,832M | $1,052M |\n| Connectivity | $2,455M | $3,498M | $4,178M | $1,332M |\n| AI | $463M | $5,633M | $12,727M | $7,723M |\n| **Total** | **$4,415M** | **$11,163M** | **$20,737M** | **$10,107M** |\n\n- AI capex has grown ~27× from 2023 to 2025 and the Q1 2026 run-rate ($7,723M) annualizes to ~$30.9B, which would exceed the combined capex of Space and Connectivity for all of 2025.\n- Space capex is accelerating due to Starship launch site infrastructure.\n- Connectivity capex is growing steadily but at a far more moderate pace than AI.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Summary of Strategic Profitability Dynamics\n\n1. **Connectivity is the financial backbone.** It is the only segment generating positive operating income and positive Adjusted EBITDA in every period. Its profitability and growth are funding investments in the other two segments. In 2025, Connectivity\'s $7,168M Adjusted EBITDA exceeded the total consolidated Adjusted EBITDA of $6,584M.\n\n2. **Space is in a deliberate investment trough.** The segment was modestly profitable in 2023–2024 but has swung to significant losses as Starship R&D ramps. The company explicitly states that Space revenue growth will lag total company growth because internal launch capacity is being redirected to Connectivity and AI. The Q1 2026 Adjusted EBITDA turning negative ($(351)M) is a notable inflection point.\n\n3. **AI is in an aggressive build-out phase.** Revenue is growing but operating losses are widening rapidly, driven by enormous R&D and depreciation from massive capital expenditures. The segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA has gone from positive ($1,222M in 2023, though inflated by impairment add-backs) to deeply negative. The company\'s stated strategy to "prioritize growth and investment" suggests profitability is not a near-term expectation.\n\n4. **The consolidated picture masks divergent trajectories.** Total Adjusted EBITDA grew from $3,821M (2023) to $6,584M (2025), but the composition shifted dramatically. In 2023, all three segments contributed positive Adjusted EBITDA. By Q1 2026, only Connectivity is positive, and its $2,087M is being partially consumed by Space ($(351)M) and AI ($(609)M) losses, yielding consolidated Adjusted EBITDA of $1,127M — down 34.7% from Q1 2025\'s $1,730M.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=79.921,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
