mes:\n\n- Terminal output has been scaled to **approximately 200,000 terminals per week**.\n- The company states it plans to "continue to further scale production significantly."\n- This figure represents manufacturing throughput, not disclosed shipment or deployment volumes.\n\n**No specific terminal shipment volumes are disclosed.**\n\n## Satellite Replacement Rates\n\n**No explicit satellite replacement rate is disclosed.** However, some inferences can be drawn from the disclosed data:\n\n- The constellation composition is described as "majority composed of our second-generation, V2 Mini satellites" as of March 31, 2026.\n- Mobile satellites grew from ~360 (V1 Mobile) to ~650 (V1 Mobile) since January 2025.\n- Next-generation V3 satellites are expected to commence deployment in the second half of 2026 via Starship.\n- A single Starship launch is expected to deploy up to 60 V3 satellites, representing a "twenty-fold increase in Starlink downlink capacity deployed relative to a Falcon 9 launch."\n\nThe filing does not provide a formal satellite replacement rate, deorbit schedule, or average useful life metric for the constellation.\n\n## Capacity Utilization Metrics\n\n**No explicit capacity utilization metric is disclosed.** The filing references capacity in qualitative and design-specification terms:\n\n- "Launching and operating higher-throughput satellites supported Starlink\'s service quality and customer reach by increasing available network capacity and improving service consistency during peak usage periods."\n- V3 satellites are "designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite."\n- No metric is provided for utilized vs. available capacity, network utilization percentage, or bandwidth utilization rates.\n\n## Customer Concentration\n\n**No customer concentration is disclosed for the Connectivity segment.** The filing describes the customer base in categorical terms:\n\n- **Consumer** customers (Starlink Consumer Broadband)\n- **Enterprise** customers ("Increasing Enterprise Customer Adoption" section discusses growth opportunities)\n- **Government** customers\n\nHowever, no percentage of revenue from the largest customer, top 5 customers, or any concentration ratio is disclosed in the provided chunks. The filing notes that Starlink Subscribers are defined as accounts that "do not have a direct, negotiated agreement with the Starlink sales team," which by definition excludes enterprise/government contracts from the subscriber count — but no concentration data is provided for those negotiated agreements either.\n\n## Financial KPIs for the Connectivity Segment\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue | $3,257M | $11,387M | $7,599M | $3,869M |\n| Income from operations | $1,188M | $4,423M | $2,006M | $469M |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $2,087M | $7,168M | N/D | N/D |\n| YoY revenue growth (2025) | — | 49.8% | — | — |\n| YoY operating income growth (2025) | — | 120.4% | — | — |\n| YoY Adj. EBITDA growth (2025) | — | 86.2% | — | — |\n| Capital expenditures | $1,332M (Q1 2026) | $4,178M | $3,498M | $2,455M |\n| Depreciation & amortization | N/D | $2,376M | $1,508M | $884M |\n| Share-based compensation | N/D | $369M | $296M | $249M |\n\n## Summary of Gaps\n\nThe following metrics are **not disclosed** in the provided chunks:\n\n- **Terminal shipment volumes** (only production capacity of ~200K/week is disclosed)\n- **Satellite replacement rates or average satellite useful life**\n- **Capacity utilization** (no utilized vs. available bandwidth metric)\n- **Customer concentration** (no top-customer or percentage-of-revenue disclosure)\n- **Churn rate** for Starlink Subscribers\n- **ARPU value** (referenced as a KPI but not quantified)\n- **Enterprise vs. consumer vs. government revenue split**\n- **Geographic revenue breakdown** beyond the aggregate country count',
